        theory: 'This section explores the fundamental concepts of work, various forms of energy, power, and their conservation principles. Key concepts include:\n- Work Done by a Force: Work done by a constant force (W = F·d = Fdcosθ) and by a variable force (W = ∫F·dx). Graphical interpretation of work (area under F-x graph). Work done by conservative and non-conservative forces.\n- Kinetic Energy: Relation to motion (K.E. = ½mv²). Work-Energy Theorem: Net work done on an object (by all forces, conservative and non-conservative) equals its change in kinetic energy.\n- Potential Energy: Concept of potential energy associated with conservative forces. Change in potential energy (ΔU = -Wc, where Wc is work done by conservative force). \n  - Gravitational potential energy (mgh near Earth\'s surface, and -GMm/r for general cases).\n  - Elastic potential energy in a spring (½kx²).\n- Conservative and Non-Conservative Forces: Properties, examples, and their role in energy conservation. Path independence/dependence of work done.\n- Conservation of Mechanical Energy: Principle (K + U = constant) and applications when only conservative forces are acting. Modification when non-conservative forces (like friction) are present (Wnc = ΔK + ΔU).\n- Power: Average power (P_avg = ΔW/Δt) and instantaneous power (P_inst = dW/dt = F·v). Units of power (Watt, horsepower).\n- Collisions: Elastic and inelastic collisions in one and two dimensions. Coefficient of restitution (e = relative velocity of separation / relative velocity of approach). Conservation of linear momentum in all collisions. Conservation of kinetic energy in perfectly elastic collisions. Analysis of head-on and oblique collisions.',
