        theory: 'This comprehensive section covers the behavior and properties of light, treating it both as rays (Geometrical Optics) and as waves (Wave Optics). Key areas include:\n- Geometrical Optics:\n  - Reflection of Light: Laws of reflection. Reflection at plane and spherical mirrors (concave and convex). Mirror formula (1/v + 1/u = 1/f), magnification (m = -v/u = h_i/h_o). Sign conventions.\n  - Refraction of Light: Laws of refraction (Snell\'s Law: n₁sin i = n₂sin r). Refraction at plane surfaces, apparent depth and shift, total internal reflection and its applications (optical fibers, mirages, prisms). Refraction through prisms, angle of deviation, dispersion of light, condition for minimum deviation.\n  - Refraction at Spherical Surfaces and Lenses: Refraction at a single spherical surface (n₂/v - n₁/u = (n₂-n₁)/R). Thin lens formula (1/v - 1/u = 1/f), lens maker\'s formula (1/f = (μ-1)(1/R₁ - 1/R₂)), magnification (m = v/u), power of a lens. Combination of thin lenses in contact and separated by a distance. Silvering of lenses.\n  - Optical Instruments: Human eye (brief structure and defects - myopia, hypermetropia, presbyopia, astigmatism and their correction). Simple microscope, compound microscope (magnifying power, resolving power). Astronomical telescope (reflecting and refracting types - magnifying power, resolving power).\n- Wave Optics:\n  - Huygens\' Principle: Wavefronts (spherical, planar, cylindrical) and wavelets. Explanation of reflection and refraction of plane waves at a plane surface using Huygens\' principle.\n  - Interference: Coherent and incoherent sources. Principle of superposition. Young\'s double-slit experiment (YDSE): derivation of fringe width (β = λD/d), conditions for constructive and destructive interference, intensity distribution. Interference in thin films (due to reflected and transmitted light - conditions for maxima and minima).\n  - Diffraction: Concept of diffraction, difference from interference. Fraunhofer diffraction due to a single slit: position of minima and maxima, width of central maximum. Resolving power of optical instruments (microscope and telescope).\n  - Polarization: Concept of polarization, plane-polarized light, unpolarized light. Methods of polarization (reflection - Brewster\'s law: μ = tan ip, scattering, selective absorption - polaroids). Malus\'s Law (I = I₀cos²θ). Double refraction.',
