        theory: 'This section explores the vast variety of life forms, their classification, and systematic organization. Key concepts include:\n- What is living?: Defining properties of living organisms (growth, reproduction, metabolism, cellular organization, consciousness, self-replication, self-organization, interaction and emergence).\n- Diversity in the living world: Need for classification. Taxonomy and Systematics. Basic concepts of nomenclature (binomial nomenclature by Carolus Linnaeus), rules of nomenclature. ICBN, ICZN.\n- Taxonomic categories: Species, genus, family, order, class, phylum/division, kingdom - hierarchical arrangement with examples.\n- Tools for study of taxonomy: Herbarium, botanical gardens, museum, zoological parks, key (taxonomic aids).\n- Five Kingdom Classification (R.H. Whittaker): Monera (Archaebacteria, Eubacteria), Protista (Chrysophytes, Dinoflagellates, Euglenoids, Slime moulds, Protozoans), Fungi (Phycomycetes, Ascomycetes, Basidiomycetes, Deuteromycetes) - salient features, characteristics, and examples of each kingdom.\n- Viruses, Viroids, Prions, and Lichens: Brief account of their structure, characteristics, and significance.\n- Plant Kingdom: Salient features and classification of plants into major groups - Algae (Chlorophyceae, Phaeophyceae, Rhodophyceae), Bryophytes (Liverworts, Mosses), Pteridophytes (Psilopsida, Lycopsida, Sphenopsida, Pteropsida), Gymnosperms, and Angiosperms. Life cycles in plants (haplontic, diplontic, haplodiplontic).\n- Animal Kingdom: Salient features and classification of animals- Non-chordates up to phyla level (Porifera, Cnidaria, Ctenophora, Platyhelminthes, Aschelminthes, Annelida, Arthropoda, Mollusca, Echinodermata, Hemichordata) and Chordates up to classes level (Cyclostomata, Chondrichthyes, Osteichthyes, Amphibia, Reptilia, Aves, Mammalia). Basis of classification (levels of organization, symmetry, coelom, segmentation, notochord).',
